[424.015847, "o", "BUG REPORT: FRAUD DETECTION PIPELINE\r\n====================================\r\n\r\n1. Target/Data Leakage in StandardScaler:\r\n   - Why it's wrong: The original pipeline applied `StandardScaler.fit_transform` on the entire dataset (both train and validation sets) before splitting. This allows statistical properties of the validation set (mean and standard deviation) to leak into the training process, leading to optimistic but unrealistic evaluation metrics.\r\n   - How it was fixed: We completely removed `StandardScaler`. For tree-based models like XGBoost, scaling is unnecessary because they are scale-invariant.\r\n\r\n2. Arbitrary Imputation (-999) combined with StandardScaler Distortion:\r\n   - Why it's wrong: Replacing missing values with `-999` and then applying `StandardScaler` distorts the numeric features and shifts the arbitrary placeholder to a different, non-standard floating point value. This compromises split searches in tree models.\r\n   - How it was fixed: Removed both the `-999` imputation and the `StandardScaler`. XGBoost natively and optimally handles missing (NaN) values without any imputation.\r\n\r\n3. Non-Temporal Random Split:\r\n   - Why it's wrong: Credit card transaction data is chronological (indicated by the `TransactionDT` column). A random train-test split causes temporal data leakage by using future transactions to predict past ones. This fails to reflect real-world performance where the model must generalize to the future.\r\n   - How it was fixed: Sorted the dataset by `TransactionDT` and performed a temporal split (first 80% for training, last 20% for validation).\r\n\r\n4. Information Loss from Dropped Categorical Columns:\r\n   - Why it's wrong: Highly informative categorical features (`ProductCD`, `card4`, and `card6`) were completely dropped, removing critical context like the transaction product type, the card brand, and the card type.\r\n   - How it was fixed: Retained these categorical columns and encoded them using One-Hot Encoding (`pd.get_dummies`) to capture brand and product patterns.\r\n\r\n5. Suboptimal Evaluation Metric:\r\n   - Why it's wrong: The XGBClassifier used `eval_metric=\"rmse\"` (Root Mean Squared Error), which is not suitable for evaluating binary classification and fraud detection models.\r\n   - How it was fixed: Configured XGBoost with `eval_metric=\"auc\"`, which aligns with the evaluation of fraud detection metrics.\r\n\u001b[?2004hroot@0d5e255b62ea:/workspace# "]
